Jan 22 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  HUGE CASH PILE PUTS RECOVERY IN HANDS OF THE FEW (http://link.reuters.com/quz26v)  INSURERS DASH GOVERNMENT HOPES OF EARLY PRODUCTS FOR ELDERLY CARE (http://link.reuters.com/ruz26v)  CITY BANKERS WARN AGAINST UK'S POTENTIAL LOSS OF INFLUENCE IN EU (http://link.reuters.com/suz26v)  BC PARTNERS CONSIDERS 1 BLN POUNDS PHONES4U LISTING (http://link.reuters.com/tuz26v)  P2P LENDERS BANKROLL DEVELOPMENT OF NEW HOMES (http://link.reuters.com/vuz26v)  Overview  A third of the largest non-financial companies of the world have an unspent cash pile of $2.8 trillion, which has been accumulating since the financial crisis, a study by Deloitte [DLTE.UL] reveals.  Long-term care products for the elderly are currently limited, and would be encouraged, the British care and support minister and the Association of British insurers said in a joint statement on Tuesday. Companies such as Aviva <AV.L>, Aegon <AEGN.AS>, Legal & General <LGEN.L> however are yet to suggest that there would be any new launches in the market at the moment.  Citigroup Inc <C.N> has warned against the United Kingdom opting out of the European Union, saying such a move could hurt the British economy and reduce investment from international companies.  British electrical good provider Phones4U is expected to be floated by private equity firm BC Partners for an initial public offering on the London Stock Exchange that would value the company to up to 1 billion pounds.